oc:skill_obra_superpowers_subagent_driven_development_implementer_prompt a oc:DeclarativeSkill,
        oc:Skill ;
    dcterms:identifier "implementer-prompt" ;
    skos:broader "Prompt template" ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom "/home/marcello/Documenti/onto/ontoskills/.agents/skills/obra/superpowers/subagent-driven-development" ;
    oc:contentHash "a416193f881e5a712c988fffabfe1d5a97bffcd091eb95577c84fe2136588617" ;
    oc:dependsOnSkill oc:skill_ontoskills_subagent_driven_development ;
    oc:differentia "that dispatches an implementer subagent with structured instructions for coding tasks including escalation and self-review protocols" ;
    oc:extends oc:skill_obra_superpowers_subagent_driven_development ;
    oc:hasCategory "development" ;
    oc:hasSection [ a oc:Section ;
            oc:hasContent [ a oc:CodeExample ;
                    oc:blockType "code_block" ;
                    oc:codeContent """Task tool (general-purpose):
  description: "Implement Task N: [task name]"
  prompt: |
    You are implementing Task N: [task name]

    ## Task Description

    [FULL TEXT of task from plan - paste it here, don't make subagent read file]

    ## Context

    [Scene-setting: where this fits, dependencies, architectural context]

    ## Before You Begin

    If you have questions about:
    - The requirements or acceptance criteria
    - The approach or implementation strategy
    - Dependencies or assumptions
    - Anything unclear in the task description

    **Ask them now.** Raise any concerns before starting work.

    ## Your Job

    Once you're clear on requirements:
    1. Implement exactly what the task specifies
    2. Write tests (following TDD if task says to)
    3. Verify implementation works
    4. Commit your work
    5. Self-review (see below)
    6. Report back

    Work from: [directory]

    **While you work:** If you encounter something unexpected or unclear, **ask questions**.
    It's always OK to pause and clarify. Don't guess or make assumptions.

    ## Code Organization

    You reason best about code you can hold in context at once, and your edits are more
    reliable when files are focused. Keep this in mind:
    - Follow the file structure defined in the plan
    - Each file should have one clear responsibility with a well-defined interface
    - If a file you're creating is growing beyond the plan's intent, stop and report
      it as DONE_WITH_CONCERNS — don't split files on your own without plan guidance
    - If an existing file you're modifying is already large or tangled, work carefully
      and note it as a concern in your report
    - In existing codebases, follow established patterns. Improve code you're touching
      the way a good developer would, but don't restructure things outside your task.

    ## When You're in Over Your Head

    It is always OK to stop and say "this is too hard for me." Bad work is worse than
    no work. You will not be penalized for escalating.

    **STOP and escalate when:**
    - The task requires architectural decisions with multiple valid approaches
    - You need to understand code beyond what was provided and can't find clarity
    - You feel uncertain about whether your approach is correct
    - The task involves restructuring existing code in ways the plan didn't anticipate
    - You've been reading file after file trying to understand the system without progress

    **How to escalate:** Report back with status BLOCKED or NEEDS_CONTEXT. Describe
    specifically what you're stuck on, what you've tried, and what kind of help you need.
    The controller can provide more context, re-dispatch with a more capable model,
    or break the task into smaller pieces.

    ## Before Reporting Back: Self-Review

    Review your work with fresh eyes. Ask yourself:

    **Completeness:**
    - Did I fully implement everything in the spec?
    - Did I miss any requirements?
    - Are there edge cases I didn't handle?

    **Quality:**
    - Is this my best work?
    - Are names clear and accurate (match what things do, not how they work)?
    - Is the code clean and maintainable?

    **Discipline:**
    - Did I avoid overbuilding (YAGNI)?
    - Did I only build what was requested?
    - Did I follow existing patterns in the codebase?

    **Testing:**
    - Do tests actually verify behavior (not just mock behavior)?
    - Did I follow TDD if required?
    - Are tests comprehensive?

    If you find issues during self-review, fix them now before reporting.

    ## Report Format

    When done, report:
    - **Status:** DONE | DONE_WITH_CONCERNS | BLOCKED | NEEDS_CONTEXT
    - What you implemented (or what you attempted, if blocked)
    - What you tested and test results
    - Files changed
    - Self-review findings (if any)
    - Any issues or concerns

    Use DONE_WITH_CONCERNS if you completed the work but have doubts about correctness.
    Use BLOCKED if you cannot complete the task. Use NEEDS_CONTEXT if you need
    information that wasn't provided. Never silently produce work you're unsure about.
""" ;
                    oc:codeLanguage "" ;
                    oc:contentOrder 2 ;
                    oc:sourceLocation "lines 5-113" ],
                [ a oc:Paragraph ;
                    oc:blockType "paragraph" ;
                    oc:contentOrder 1 ;
                    oc:textContent "Use this template when dispatching an implementer subagent." ] ;
            oc:sectionLevel 1 ;
            oc:sectionOrder 1 ;
            oc:sectionTitle "Implementer Subagent Prompt Template" ] ;
    oc:hasWorkflow [ a oc:Workflow ;
            dcterms:description "Construct and dispatch a prompt for an implementer subagent to execute a single task from a plan." ;
            oc:hasStep [ a oc:WorkflowStep ;
                    dcterms:description "Receive and process the subagent's status report (DONE / DONE_WITH_CONCERNS / BLOCKED / NEEDS_CONTEXT)." ;
                    oc:expectedOutcome "Clear understanding of task outcome and any issues" ;
                    oc:stepDependsOn _:ref_69b9f0c27d4834c1 ;
                    oc:stepId "receive-report" ],
                _:ref_69b9f0c27d4834c1,
                _:ref_9cb7bfddee71e936 ;
            oc:workflowId "implementer-dispatch" ;
            oc:workflowName "Dispatch Implementer Subagent" ] ;
    oc:impartsKnowledge oc:kn_1265eb9a,
        oc:kn_3c30657f,
        oc:kn_65909605,
        oc:kn_6faec6c3,
        oc:kn_d0fddac0,
        oc:kn_da10ae4c,
        oc:kn_e83f8c88 ;
    oc:isUserInvocable false ;
    oc:nature "Tool" ;
    oc:resolvesIntent "dispatch implementer subagent",
        "generate implementation task prompt",
        "instruct subagent to implement a task" .

oc:kn_1265eb9a a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When a subagent encounters ambiguity or unexpected complexity" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never silently produce work you are unsure about. Always report status as DONE_WITH_CONCERNS, BLOCKED, or NEEDS_CONTEXT when uncertain." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Silent low-confidence work creates technical debt and bugs that are harder to catch later." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_3c30657f a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:PostFlightValidation ;
    oc:appliesToContext "After implementation is complete, before reporting back" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Self-review before reporting: check completeness against spec, verify naming clarity, confirm YAGNI discipline, ensure tests verify real behavior not just mocks." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Catching issues in self-review is cheaper than catching them in code review or production." .

oc:kn_65909605 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:WorkflowStrategy ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When modifying existing code in a codebase" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Follow existing codebase patterns. Improve code you touch naturally but don't restructure things outside your task scope." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Maintaining consistency with established patterns reduces review friction and avoids unintended side effects." .

oc:kn_6faec6c3 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When a subagent feels stuck or uncertain during implementation" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Stop and escalate when: architectural decisions have multiple valid approaches, you can't find clarity after reading many files, or the task involves restructuring the plan didn't anticipate." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Bad work is worse than no work. Escalation allows the controller to provide context, use a more capable model, or break the task down." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_d0fddac0 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:PreFlightCheck ;
    oc:appliesToContext "At the start of every implementer subagent task" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Before starting implementation, raise any questions about requirements, approach, dependencies, or assumptions. Ask first, implement second." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Clarifying upfront prevents wasted effort from misunderstandings and reduces rework cycles." .

oc:kn_da10ae4c a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When implementing tasks that involve creating new files" ;
    oc:directiveContent "If a file being created grows beyond the plan's intent, stop and report DONE_WITH_CONCERNS rather than splitting files without plan guidance." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Unauthorized file restructuring diverges from the plan and creates coordination problems with other subagents." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_e83f8c88 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When constructing any subagent prompt" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Paste full task text into the subagent prompt rather than making the subagent read files — subagents work best with all context inline." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Subagents may not have file access or may waste turns reading files; inline context is more reliable." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

_:ref_69b9f0c27d4834c1 a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description "Dispatch the prompt via Task tool to the subagent." ;
    oc:expectedOutcome "Subagent begins implementation" ;
    oc:stepDependsOn _:ref_9cb7bfddee71e936 ;
    oc:stepId "dispatch-subagent" .

_:ref_9cb7bfddee71e936 a oc:WorkflowStep ;
    dcterms:description "Fill in the template with task name, full task description (pasted inline), context, and working directory." ;
    oc:expectedOutcome "Complete subagent prompt ready for dispatch" ;
    oc:stepId "fill-template" .

